ench, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Rabbitt","meanings":["English: from the Middle English male personal name <i>Rabbode</i>, <i>Radboda</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Radbodo</i>, from elements meaning ‘counsel’ + ‘messenger’).","English: from the personal name <i>Robet</i> or <i>Robot</i>, diminutives of <i>Rob</i> (see   Robert  ).","English: nickname from late Middle English <i>rabet</i> ‘young rabbit’. This word is not recorded until <i>c.</i> 1398, the usual Middle English word for ‘rabbit’ being <i>cony</i> (see   Coney  )."]},{"name":"McRobbie","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire): patronymic meaning ‘son of Robbie’, from the personal name <i>Robbie</i>, a Scottish pet form of   Robert  , with the Gaelic prefix <i>mac</i> ‘son of’."]},{"name":"Rabjohn","meanings":["English (Devon, Essex): from the Middle English personal name <i>Robechon</i> (of Norman French origin: Old Picard <i>Robichon</i>, Old French <i>Robeçun</i>), a double diminutive of <i>Rob</i>, a pet form of   Robert  , altered by folk etymology to <i>Robjohn</i> and <i>Rabjohn</i>."]},{"name":"Nabb","meanings":["English (Lancashire): topographic name for someone who lived by a <i>nab</i>, Middle English <i>nabbe</i> ‘hillock, knoll’ (Old Norse <i>nabbi</i> ‘projecting peak, hill’), or a habitational name from any of the many minor places in northern and eastern England named with this word, for example Whalley Nab in Blackburn (Lancashire), Nab Scar in Rydal (Westmorland), and The Nab in Burgh Saint Margaret (Norfolk).","English (Lancashire): alternatively, it may be from the Middle English personal names <i>Nabb</i> and <i>Napp</i>, which are probably parallels to <i>Nobb</i> and <i>Nopp</i>, pet forms of   Robert  . Compare   Nobbs  .","Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Aba(dh)</b> ‘son of the abbot’, see   McNab  ."]},{"name":"Probert","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Roppert</i> ‘son of Robert’(see   Robert  )."]},{"name":"Rabb","meanings":["Scottish and English (Lancashire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Rab(b)</i>, a pet form of   Robert   with unrounding of the first vowel. Compare   Robb  .","Hungarian: variant of   Rab  ."]},{"name":"Rapson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Rab(b)</i> (a pet form of   Robert   with unrounding of the first vowel) + <i>-son</i>, with devoicing of /b/ to /p/. Compare   Robson   and   Rabb  ."]},{"name":"McCobb","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Mac Hob</b>, ‘son of <i>Hob</i> ‘, an English pet form of   Robert  . Compare   Hobson  ."]},{"name":"McRoberts","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Roibeirt</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelic form of the personal name   Robert  , with English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Robin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Emile, Marcel, Achille, Armand, Arnaud, Camille, Julien, Michel, Normand.","French, Breton, Scottish, English, and German: from the personal name <i>Robin</i>, a pet form of   Robert  , composed of the short form <i>Rob</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-in</i>.","Slovenian: topographic name derived from <i>rob</i> ‘edge, border’ (see   Robar  )."]}]},{"name":"Hwen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Gwendolen   or   Gwenllian  , or an independent name from <i>gwen</i>, the feminine form of <i>gwyn</i> ‘white, fair; blessed, holy’. It was borne by a 5th-century saint, aunt of  St David  and mother of the minor saints Cybi and Cadfan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hwen ferch Robert was born in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with Tudor Ab Ieuan."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1236–Female":"1236–Surnud","1432–Female":"1432–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","ABT    1432":"umbes 1432","1236":"1236","1432":"1432","1396":"1396","about 1236":"umbes 1236","of Segrwyd,Llanrhaeadr-yng-,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Cae'rgerrig,Llangwm,Denbighshire,Wales":"Llangwm, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Uwch Dulas cmt,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1236–Female":"1236–Kuollut","1432–Female":"1432–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","ABT    1432":"noin 1432","1236":"1236","1432":"1432","1396":"1396","about 1236":"noin 1236","of Segrwyd,Llanrhaeadr-yng-,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Cae'rgerrig,Llangwm,Denbighshire,Wales":"Llangwm, Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of,Uwch Dulas cmt,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1396–Male":"1396–Décédé","1236–Female":"1236–Décédée","1432–Female":"1432–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","ABT 